<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Middle Earth a Multicultural Society<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.58)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6439'>clarrie " DLOTSuckers" brown</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6439&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 25, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> When most players go to make a Shadow deck in Lord of The Rings, they think of which side can screw with an opponent&#8217;s fellowship the most while complementing their own Free People design in the best way possible. <br />
<br />
For example, if you wanted to be able to cycle through your deck quickly and have access to particular cards in your deck you&#8217;d like play Moria due to their renowned Scavenger/scimitar/armory combo to draw like a mad man. If you aimed to smash the enemy when he/she is weakest, before they have established themselves, you&#8217;d play Nazgul to cause lots of early damage and overwhelming. If direct damage or discardation was built into your Free People deck, then Sauron can do that to great affect also. If pure beats are needed to entangle the enemy while you race home then the Uruk-hai are you friends.<br />
 <br />
But often you&#8217;ll find that the strength of one Shadow culture is missing in another. While Moria is widely known to be archery fodder, Nazgul and uruks have the capabilities to hurt a Free People archery strategy. While Nazgul are hard pressed to stack up the burdens, that make available their most powerful abilities, Sauron Orcs have many ways of effectively and efficiently piling the burdens on Frodo.<br />
<br />
So what stops you, as the deck builder, crossing the boundaries of Minion culture limits and accessing the abilities of multiple cultures in the same deck (and I don&#8217;t just mean Skulkers in a Nazgul deck). This article will highlight the best combinations of Shadow minions and hopefully give some of you a few ideas how the enhance your minion decks to really put the hurt of the opponents fellowship.<br />
<br />
NAZGUL and SAURON: First lets establish the power of the Nazgul. We all know they come out early, are high in strength and vitality and mostly fierce. However they are very high in shadow cost and towards the end of the game they are often hard pressed to puncture a fully armed fellowship, particularly against A Rangers Versatility, as you&#8217;ll rarely be able to play more than 2 at a time. The other problem is that they require a lot of support cards both events and conditions. Even if you don&#8217;t run the Blade Tip/Black Breath variant, you need plenty of Relentless Charges, All Blades perish and something to increase their strength, Nazgul swords, Black Steeds or adding cards like All Veils Removed. Now lets think outside the box for a minute. Enquea, Toldea, and the soon to be release Twilight Nelya are all very nasty in and of themselves without the need for other cards, all they need is burdens. Nazgul swords become crazy when you can spot only 3 burdens. However cards like In The Wake of The Ring Wraith are fairly ineffective at accumulating burdens quickly.<br />
<br />
    Now lets take a look at Sauron Orcs. Sauron minions have a variety of nasty support cards, but in and of themselves tend to be lower Strength and high in Twilight cost (up until Site 6). Many of them do possess a cruel ability to &#8216;exert to wound&#8217; meaning they will usually get at least one wound on who ever they skirmish. Combined with the Orc Bowmen/ Under the Watchful Eye combo they can do much damage if it comes out quickly. The card Hate is excellent for surprise kills on the opposing fellowship. Unfortunately, they are crippled by Sleep Cahradras and at this point in the game there is little one can do to prevent it devastating your conditions.  Towards the end of the game (sites 7-9) they can swarm surprisingly well though, particularly at the site 9 Tol Brandir (trackers from discard pile). What makes Sauron so powerful supporting Nazgul is the cards, Thin and Stretched and Desperate Defense of The Ring. Both are excellent at dealing out burdens with minimum effort and expense. If you play these without the Bowmen/UTWE combo, Sleep Cahradras will be less devastating and you&#8217;ll most likely have multiple copies to play after the first have been discarded. Athelas could be a pest, but since the decline of Tip/Breath decks very few decks play more than 1 or 2 Athelas. Beauty is Fading can be used to deal with that and other companion possessions like Aragorns Bow and Glamdring anyway.<br />
 Combining these 2 culture&#8217;s strengths and weaknesses we have we have a minion side that can fighter effectively at sites 2-9, deal a lot of direct damage (especially on archers) increase Burdens faster than the opponent can remove them (hopefully) and gain great Benefits from those burdens. Once 4 burdens are accumulated Ulaire Toldea can assign himself to Sam and kill him, making the burdens VERY difficult to remove. Moreover, the majority of the minions are quite high in strength (most Nazgul, Morgul Hunter, Band of the Eye, War Band) and the mighty Enduring Evil can make that a mute point anyhow. On The Flip side, such a deck will be fairly high in Shadow cost to operate, and the size of the deck require to fit it all in could be a tookunky. So lets break it down:<br />
<br />
Nazgul minions x10-12<br />
Sauron minions x8-11<br />
Burden conditions x4<br />
Relentless charge x3<br />
Nazgul Sword x2-4<br />
Hate x2-4<br />
Enduring Evil x1<br />
<br />
TOTAL 30-38<br />
<br />
So playing off of these rough numbers you could easily have the most tight or most chunky deck you want depending on your tastes! Try to keep it well fewer than 40 though. This should help provide a basic structure for you next time you build a deck. <br />
<br />
<br />
NAZGUL and MORIA: I think its safe to say that of the 4 Shadow sides Nazgul and Moria swarms are the 2 most popular (though not necessarily the most powerful). Both cultures possess versatility and efficiency and can made effective without loads of rares, though they do help. Having already outlined the strengths and weaknesses of Ringwraiths I&#8217;ll concentrate on Moria.<br />
	The best thing about Moria is they&#8217;re cheap. Lots of Moria minions can be laid down with a minimum of Twilight pool, in fact some even add to it. They possess the unique ability to create a cycling engine that essential allows greater access to the cards in your Deck than via normal means (this is of course the scavenger/scimitar/armory combo). The thing about Moria orcs and goblins is that they lack strength and vitality. Yes many can hit the table but whether and survive the archery phase is another matter entirely. Those that do often get Skooled but a big mean Gandalf, Friend to the Shirefolk. Goblin Armories can help deflect archery but they are often the first things to make an opponent dive through his deck looking for Sleep Cahradras. And then there is the Cave Troll. Widely believed to be the most Powerful minion in the game (until the Balrog becomes legal). 15 strength, 4 vitality, Fierce and Damage +1 he can give as good as he gets. At present his one great weakness was Fellowship aimed archery. When Mines of Moria sends him his Chain all that will change.<br />
 	So in summary, Moria orcs break down like this:<br />
 Pros; Cheap, increase twilight pool, greater access to Draw deck, one big ugly Troll. <br />
Cons; Archery fodder, difficult to break a large fellowship, difficult to avoid getting slain by an event rich, micro fellowship (PAtHS, Valiant Man etc)<br />
<br />
	So how does Moria pair up with Nazgul? Surprising well. Forget getting those burdens on though, but expect some serious carnage to be inflicted on the opponent. <br />
Moria provides the deep Pool and Nazgul provide the Increased Archery protection that Moria sorely needs. In the end it equates to a pure beats deck. A well-placed Relentless charge renders Aragorn and Legolas helpless and the little Goblins with their scimitars run in and pile up on Frodo. Though PAtHS still hurts a fierce Nazgul or 2 backing up the orcs are very hard to move against. The best about this sort of combination is you can keep up the pressure, even if you don&#8217;t overwhelm the opponent, you fellowship should be able to win the race with ease!! Though you can run out of steam at site 9, this deck type is VERY solid and I recommend it to new and veteran players alike. Less rare cards are needed to be effective. If you have them though, the Cave Troll and Attea/Witch-king totally wreck.<br />
To give you some ideas my deck structure would look like this:<br />
	<br />
	Nazgul minions x6-8<br />
	Moria Minions x14-18<br />
	Moria conditions x 3-6<br />
	Relentless Charge x3-4<br />
	Goblin scimitars x4<br />
	Other Events x 2-4<br />
<br />
	TOTAL: 35-40 <br />
<br />
Obviously with Moria you want a big deck to cycle through and not burn it out by site 6 so a 35 card shadow is a good start and work from there.<br />
<br />
<br />
	NAZGUL and ISENGARD: At first glance these 2 cultures might not gel so well together and to a certain extent that is true. However they do share some common traits and if honed correctly can produce a devastating fighting unit. Both Ringwraith and Isengard possess the best anti-archery cards at this point in the game, those being Relentless Charge and Spies of Saruman. Spies of Saruman is the best as it just stops archery altogether but is vulnerable to Albert Dreary. Nazgul have great Ally killers like Fear and Their Power is in Their Fear. Combining these cards Archery decks are hurt exponentially. Also both cultures have many Fierce minions with high Strength. Unfortunately this comes at a price and that is high shadow cost. While Uruk-hai won&#8217;t break the bank, you won&#8217;t be able get many down along side Nazgul unless the opponent has put considerably extra into the pool in his Fellowship phase, obviously something you can&#8217;t rely on. <br />
	Because Uruk-hai don&#8217;t fit perfectly with other minions, the best Uruk war machines utilize only Isengard cards to steam roll the opposition. But a powerful mutt squad of Uruk-hai and Nazgul is still very achievable. In this case I would focus on a Nazgul half with most of their support cards and use the Uruk-hai as the follow through with their big Damage +1 and anti-archery stuff. Why these decks DO work is while Nazgul are weak towards the last couple site, Uruk-hai just get better the closer you are to the end. I&#8217;d suggest using the cheapest Uruks like Soldiers, Fighters, Warriors and Messengers if you play Weather conditions. I suggest a deck something like this:<br />
	Nazgul minions x8-12<br />
 	Uruk-hai minions x8-10<br />
	Isengard conditions x4-6<br />
	Nazgul Events (R/C & Fear) x4-5<br />
	Events x2 (Savagery to Match Their Numbers)<br />
<br />
TOTAL: 30-34<br />
<br />
You&#8217;d probably want to keep it tight, as close to 30 as possible to get access to the cards you need when you need them.<br />
<br />
<br />
	SAURON and ISENGARD:  This cross-cultural deck can be VERY funny to play and extremely unfunny for your opponent. The theme-Discardation to death. Both Uruks and Sauron orcs have lots of simple and effective ways to make your opponent discard cards from their hand and Draw deck. The Uruk Soldier discards a card from top of draw deck when played, the Rager discard 2 when he wins a skirmish and the Uruk sword (and soon Lurtz&#8217;s Sword) has the same effect. This can lead to vital cards flying off the top at the opponents despair. Sauron Discardation has even worse psychological effects on the opponent, as the cards must come from hand AT RANDOM! The Orc Inquisitor forced one card from hand when played and the Tower Lieutenant forces 2 when he wins skirmishes. Desperate Measures is a very broken card. &#8220;Remove a burden to make the Free People player discard 5 cards from his Draw deck&#8221; &#8211;ouch. Play 4 of those In a game and you can be sure the opponent will be burned out before the end. Previously mentioned, Desperate <br />
Defense of the Ring forces either a burden to be added or the opponent discards 3 cards from hand, a bad position to be put. Orc butchery discards 3 cards off the top for each character in the dead pile. Alive and Unspoiled is much like the Mirror of Galadriel, except it relies on burdens.<br />
	Discardation is one of the nastiest strategies in the game at this point and Sauron/Uruk-hai minions are the way to do it. Back it with Galadriel and The Mirror on the Free People side for ultimate discarding possibilities. <br />
The main weakness of these minions is that they come out at site 5 and 6 and are fairly expensive to put into play. But that&#8217;s not the point. As long as you keep the opponent from getting what he want sin his hand, he should be unable to keep you from snagging victory. Here is a skeleton deck to get you thinking<br />
<br />
	Uruk Soldier x4<br />
	Rager x3<br />
	Inquisitor x4<br />
	Tower Lieutenant x3 <br />
	Desparate Measures x4<br />
 	Desparate Defense of the Ring x3<br />
	Other Big Minions x6-10 <br />
	Hate x2<br />
<br />
	TOTAL: 32-36<br />
<br />
MORIA and SAURON: Never seen a Moria/Sauron deck? Probably with good cause. These 2 cultures do nothing to compliment each other. One comes out very early the other comes out very later. Moria benefits nothing from burdens and Sauron will get no help from Moria in that endeavor.  Neither has any effective way of dealing with archery and are both generally low in vitality. Admittedly Sauron can help with overwhelming at the end game (via Tol Brandir), in fact that could be an avenue for exploration, one big beat down at site 9. But I&#8217;m sure if this was viable that somebody would have devised a way to mix Sauron and Moria. I sure haven&#8217;t been successful with my attempts Have YOU?<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
MORIA, ISENGARD and NAZGUL: This is an interesting combination, not least of which being that this is the only 3 way culture split that seems to work coherently (Sauron it too card intensive, for a 3 way). A recent trend has arisen where a Moria deck is used as the core race, while powerful parts of the Ringwraith and Isengard cultures are used in support for massive beat downs on the enemy fellowship. The Moria Cycle engine helps sift through for the necessary cards like Sarumans snow, Spies of Saruman and the Uruks needed to play them. These protect the goblin hordes from their greatest enemies, Aimed Archery and Power According to His Stature. The Nazgul parts are their as Backbone and provide anti ally cards like Fear to prevent any spanners in the works. A very interesting theme, and mostly unexplored at this point. <br />
	By the last few sites the shadow player has all the cards he needs to drop a bomb on his opponent, theoretically overwhelming he opponents Ring-bearer every time. Definitely a strong strategy. Check out Alex &#8220;Greedo&#8221; Tennet&#8217;s Inquest deck &#8220;Snowbomb&#8221; for a detailed example of this sort of deck type.<br />
	At this point a serious 3 culture minion deck is only in the developing stage and a 4 culture deck is virtually unheard of.<br />
<br />
<br />
CONCLUSION: I aimed to provide a comprehensive view of the possible Shadow culture combinations of Lord of The Rings; a topic I believe is understudied at present. Of course you can play single culture decks, they are undoubtedly competitive. But playing Multicultural Shadow decks increases you options and abilities to foil your opponents Fellowship.<br />
With the next expansion set nearly here and more on the way I&#8217;m sure more options for cross minion decks will increase, but at present this is what we&#8217;ve all got to work with.<br />
I hope I&#8217;ve achieved my aim and provided you all with, at the very least, an enjoyable read. At best I&#8217;ve improved your deck skills and given you some new ideas.<br />
<br />
